NPS is also an important task for the CS team. As part of this process, we need to send survey links to the relevant clients so that they can rate our service and provide feedback.

From the GPS CS perspective, the overall process works like this.

First, we obtain the raw data to determine which clients the survey should be sent to.

After we have identified the clients, we provide this information to the PCM MI team. They mainly support us in two aspects. The first is generating the encrypted email, and the second is providing the NPS survey link.

In the previous workflow, once the survey link was ready, it would be passed to the vendor. The vendor would then send the emails through ConvertLab. After the emails were sent, the vendor would provide us with a report showing which clients opened the email and which did not.

If we look closely at this workflow, the main task performed by the vendor is essentially sending emails through the ConvertLab platform. Although they also provide a report afterwards, the importance of this report is actually quite limited. What really matters to us is how to make the email sending step more efficient and more automated.

When we analyzed this process, we identified three possible options, and we explored each of them.

The first option was to keep the current process and continue using the vendor through ConvertLab. However, the main concern here is the cost. As we all know, the cost is around 10,000 RMB per month.

Because of this, this is not the option we prefer.

We also explored whether it would be possible for us to use ConvertLab directly. However, after some research, we found that the feasibility is quite low. There are several reasons for this.

First, ConvertLab is a professional marketing automation platform, and it is relatively complex to use.

Second, the license fee is not paid directly by us to the platform provider. Instead, we pay the vendor, and the vendor pays the software company.

Third, based on our discussions with the Marketing team, it is also unlikely that this license would be allocated directly to us.

Therefore, this option is not very realistic for our team.

The second option we explored was Mail Merge, which is a built-in feature in Microsoft Office.

The basic idea is to prepare a Word template and an Excel file containing the recipient information and the content that needs to be filled in. Then the Word template can be connected to Outlook through Mail Merge. Finally, the system can generate emails in bulk and send them automatically.

However, we eventually decided not to adopt this solution either, mainly because of two major limitations.

The first limitation is that we cannot send emails from the designated shared mailbox.

The second limitation is that the generation process is essentially a black box. Once the process starts, it runs from beginning to end and sends all emails automatically. There is no opportunity to pause the process and conduct another check before the emails are sent.

Because of these two issues, we decided not to proceed with the Mail Merge solution.

Given these constraints, our remaining options were quite limited. Therefore, we decided to develop a VBA tool to support this operational task.

It is important to clarify that this tool does not directly send the emails. Instead, the tool only generates email drafts.

Once the drafts are created, manual checking is still required. Someone will review the emails and then send them manually. Because of this, the operational risk is relatively low.

The workflow of this tool is quite straightforward.

First, we prepare a Word template. In this template, we can freely design the email format and content based on our needs.

Second, we define placeholders in the template. These placeholders will later be replaced with recipient information from Excel, as well as the corresponding NPS survey link.

Third, we prepare an Excel file that contains the recipient information and the survey links.

Based on this setup, the tool provides three different ways to generate email drafts.

The first option is “All”. When this button is clicked, the tool will generate drafts for all emails at once.

The second option is “Single”. In this mode, the tool will generate only one specific email draft, depending on the selected record.

The third option is “Range”. In this case, the tool will generate drafts for a selected range of records, for example from A to B.

So overall, we have three different modes to trigger the draft generation.

This is the overall solution we developed to improve the NPS email sending process.

That is all for my sharing, and I would be happy to take any questions or suggestions from the team.
